title="Proof by induction">Proof by induction</fr:link> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n=\deg (f)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Base case:</fr:strong> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n=1]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)=x-\alpha ]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha \in \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha \in \Bbbk ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Inductive case:</fr:strong> Suppose this is true for any polynomial of degree strictly less than <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{1}(x)]]></fr:tex> be an irreducible factor of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex>, we suppose <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\deg (f)=n]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F_{1}=\mathbb {F}[x]/(f_{1}(x))\cong \mathbb {F}(\alpha )]]></fr:tex> for a root <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha ]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{1}]]></fr:tex> (which is also a root of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex>).</fr:p>
<fr:p>But then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)=(x-\alpha )g(x)]]></fr:tex> for some polynomial <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g(x)]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\deg (g)<\deg (f)]]></fr:tex>. Then by the inductive hypothesis, there exists an extension <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk  / \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> over which <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g(x)]]></fr:tex> splits completely with
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[[\Bbbk  : F_{1}]\leq \deg (g)!=(n-1)!]]></fr:tex>
Then
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[[\Bbbk  : \mathbb {F}]\leq  n!]]></fr:tex>
and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> splits completely over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:tree
